success.question_text: How many passengers were on the bus when it left the city?
success.question_category_path: General Ability / Non-Verbal Reasoning / Problem Solving

stimulus_2.text:
A bus leaves the city with passengers.

At the first stop, one half of the passengers get off, and 10 get on.

At the second stop, one half of the passengers get off, and 4 get on.

There are now 16 passengers on the bus.

review_1.column_1_text: Solution

review_3.column_1_text:
Work backwards through the problem.

At the end of the journey there are 16 passengers.

As 16 – 4 = 12, there must have been 12 passengers before the last 4 got on.

Now 12 was half the number of passengers before the second stop, so there must have been 24 passengers immediately before the second stop.

As 24 – 10 = 14, there must have been 14 passengers before 10 got on at the first stop.

Now 14 was half the number of passengers before the first stop, so there must have been 28 passengers immediately before the first stop.

There were 28 passengers when the bus left the city.

(Check the answer by using 28 and working through the question.)

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Show your working so that you can check the steps you have used to arrive at your answer.

success.question_text: In the same code what does CDHQE represent?
success.question_category_path: General Ability / Non-Verbal Reasoning / Symbolic Relationships - Codes

stimulus_1.text: In a code, PLUME is represented by DLTKO.

review_1.column_1_text:
Solution

DLTKO represents PLUME.

Now P is the letter after O. L is the letter after K. U is the letter after T, M the letter after L and E the letter after D.

So the code is to reverse the letters and move forward one letter in the alphabet.

To decode CDHQE, first reverse the letter order: EQHDC.

Each letter is then replaced by the letter which follows it alphabetically.

This means the answer is FRIED.

review_2.column_1_text:
Tip

When breaking (or deciphering) codes, use what is known to find what is unknown.
